See manual_full_00_README.txt for the tier legend before reading this file. Two extra conventions used from here on, to keep PYRUN entries honest:
  - Object field access inside a PYRUN expression uses `_.get('key')` (mirrors Navigation's null-safe-on-missing-key behavior), not `_['key']` (which raises on a missing key).
  - jq's arithmetic operators (+ - * /) are polymorphic (numbers/arrays/strings/objects all behave differently). I'm NOT implementing that polymorphism generically -- each PYRUN expression below is a specific-case Python translation valid for that one example's types, not a reusable jq-operator equivalent.
  - `map(f)` examples (jq's own array-collect, single output) get plain foreach + no OUT_FMT. `.[] | f`-style examples (an actual jq stream) get foreach + OUT_FMT=STREAM. These read the same in jq but reshape differently for GOLD.

[BA-001-addition-number]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .a + 1
INPUT = {"a": 7}
GOLD = 8
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _.get('a') + 1"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[BA-002-addition-arrays]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .a + .b
INPUT = {"a": [1,2], "b": [3,4]}
GOLD = [1,2,3,4]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _.get('a') + _.get('b')"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Python list `+` happens to already mean concatenation, matches jq here.

[BA-003-addition-null]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .a + null
INPUT = {"a": 1}
GOLD = 1
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _.get('a')"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, simplified: this specific case reduces to just .a since jq's "+null" is a no-op, not a general null-coalesce translation.

[BA-004-addition-missing-field]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .a + 1
INPUT = {}
GOLD = 1
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= (_.get('a') or 0) + 1"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. `or 0` stands in for jq's "missing/null treated as 0 in +" rule -- fine for this numeric case, would misfire if .a were legitimately 0 and you cared about that distinction.

[BA-005-addition-object-merge]
LEVEL=construct
JQ = {a: 1} + {b: 2} + {c: 3} + {a: 42}
INPUT = null
GOLD = {"a": 42, "b": 2, "c": 3}
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= {**{'a':1}, **{'b':2}, **{'c':3}, **{'a':42}}"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Object merge via dict-unpack, later keys win (matches jq's "rightmost wins" rule).

[BA-006-subtraction-number]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = 4 - .a
INPUT = {"a":3}
GOLD = 1
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= 4 - _.get('a')"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[BA-007-subtraction-array]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = . - ["xml", "yaml"]
INPUT = ["xml", "yaml", "json"]
GOLD = ["json"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [x for x in _ if x not in ['xml','yaml']]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. jq's array `-` removes all occurrences of the right array's elements from the left.

[BA-008-mul-div]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = 10 / . * 3
INPUT = 5
GOLD = 6
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= 10 / _ * 3"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[BA-009-string-division-split]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = . / ", "
INPUT = "a, b,c,d, e"
GOLD = ["a","b,c,d","e"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _.split(', ')"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. jq's string "/" is split-by-separator; Python's str.split matches closely enough for this case (edge cases around leading/trailing separators may differ, untested).

[BA-010-recursive-object-merge]
LEVEL=construct
JQ = {"k": {"a": 1, "b": 2}} * {"k": {"a": 0,"c": 3}}
INPUT = null
GOLD = {"k": {"a": 0, "b": 2, "c": 3}}
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= {'k': {**{'a':1,'b':2}, **{'a':0,'c':3}}}"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, hand-unrolled: this specific test is only 1 level of nesting so I inlined the merge directly rather than writing a general recursive-merge function (still don't know if $pyrun supports multi-statement/def code -- this dodges needing that).

[BA-011-division-error-suppression]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[] | (1 / .)?
INPUT = [1,0,-1]
GOLD = [1, -1]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [1 / x for x in _ if x != 0]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM, revised: a list comprehension with an `if` clause is one Python expression, so this sidesteps needing a JFTL-native filter/select mechanism entirely -- same trick resolves curated-batch 110's "select" case (should go back and fix that one too, flagging separately).

[BA-012-abs]
LEVEL=foreach
JQ = map(abs)
INPUT = [-10, -1.1, -1e-1]
GOLD = [10,1.1,1e-1]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"value": "x"}, "body": "$pyrun= abs(_)"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM-shape-but-not-STREAM-tagged: map(f) is jq's own array-collect (one output), so no OUT_FMT here even though the template still uses foreach -- see file header note.

[BA-013-length-stream]
LEVEL=foreach
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[] | length
INPUT = [[1,2], "string", {"a":2}, null, -5]
GOLD = [2, 6, 1, 0, 5]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"value": "x"}, "body": "$pyrun= 0 if _ is None else (abs(_) if isinstance(_, (int, float)) else len(_))"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM. jq's length is type-polymorphic (string/array/object -> len, number -> abs value, null -> 0); this ternary chain covers exactly the 5 cases in this example, not every possible input type.

[BA-014-utf8bytelength]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = utf8bytelength
INPUT = "μ"
GOLD = 2
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= len(_.encode('utf-8'))"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[BA-015-keys-sorted]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = keys
INPUT = {"abc": 1, "abcd": 2, "Foo": 3}
GOLD = ["Foo", "abc", "abcd"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= sorted(_.keys())"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Python's default string sort is codepoint order too, matches jq here.

[BA-016-keys-array]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = keys
INPUT = [42,3,35]
GOLD = [0,1,2]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= list(range(len(_)))"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[BA-017-has-object]
LEVEL=foreach
JQ = map(has("foo"))
INPUT = [{"foo": 42}, {}]
GOLD = [true, false]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"value": "x"}, "body": "$pyrun= 'foo' in _"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+map (no OUT_FMT, see file header).

[BA-018-has-array]
LEVEL=foreach
JQ = map(has(2))
INPUT = [[0,1], ["a","b","c"]]
GOLD = [false, true]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"value": "x"}, "body": "$pyrun= 2 < len(_)"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+map.

[BA-019-in-object-stream]
LEVEL=foreach
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[] | in({"foo": 42})
INPUT = ["foo", "bar"]
GOLD = [true, false]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"value": "x"}, "body": "$pyrun= _ in {'foo': 42}"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM.

[BA-020-in-array]
LEVEL=foreach
JQ = map(in([0,1]))
INPUT = [2, 0]
GOLD = [false, true]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"value": "x"}, "body": "$pyrun= 0 <= _ < 2"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+map. `in([0,1])` checks whether the current value is a valid *index* into a length-2 array, i.e. in range(0,2) -- hardcoded the length here since it's a literal in the jq program, not derived from input.
